{
  "text": "We extend the model of [CITATION_1] in the following way. Schultz uses a version of the [CITATION_2] model with two consumers groups, informed and uninformed consumers. Only informed consumers are fully aware of prices charged by all firms while uninformed consumers always buy from the nearest one. The proportion of informed consumers is then taken as a measure for the transparency in the market. We follow this approach. One feature of the Salop model and of [CITATION_3] is that consumer demand for the differentiated product is inelastic. A consumer demands one single unit as long as the price is lower than the reservation value. In contrast, following [CITATION_4] , we consider a version wherein demand is price-dependent. In this setup, product variety can be excessive or insufficient.",
